.TH NAMGEN 1 "November 2023" "namgen 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
namgen \- a flexible name generator combining adjectives and nouns
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B namgen
[\fIoptions\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBnamgen\fR creates random, human‑readable identifiers by combining an
adjective and a noun.  By default the output format is
\fBadjective-noun\fR, but the separator, capitalisation and many other
behaviours can be customised via command‑line options or environment
variables.
.PP
The program reads word lists from the installed assets directory (or
from files supplied by the user), optionally filters characters, and
produces the requested number of names.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-a, \-\-adj-file \fIFILE\fR
Path to a custom adjectives file.  If omitted the program selects a file
from the assets directory (default:
\fIassets/adjectives/adjectives.list\fR).
.TP
.B \-n, \-\-noun-file \fIFILE\fR
Path to a custom nouns file.  If omitted the program selects a file
from the assets directory (default:
\fIassets/nouns/nouns.list\fR).
.TP
.B \-s, \-\-separator \fISEP\fR
String used to separate adjective and noun.  The default separator is
a hyphen (\fB-\fR).  An empty string disables the separator when used
with \fB\-\-null-separator\fR.
.TP
.B \-x, \-\-null-separator
Do not print any separator between adjective and noun.  This overrides
the value supplied with \fB\-\-separator\fR.
.TP
.B \-c, \-\-count \fICOUNT\fR
Number of names to generate.  If omitted the program defaults to the
height of the terminal (or 24 lines if the height cannot be detected).
.TP
.B \-\-capcasing, \-\-cap
Capitalize the first letter of both adjective and noun (e.g.
\fBHappyDog\fR when used with \fB\-\-null-separator\fR).
.TP
.B \-\-camelcasing, \-\-camel
Generate names in CamelCase style with only the noun capitalised
(e.g. \fBhappyDog\fR).  This option implies \fB\-\-null-separator\fR.
.TP
.B \-e, \-\-exclude \fICHARS\fR
Remove the characters listed in \fICHARS\fR from both adjective and noun
words before they are combined.  By default the characters apostrophe
(\fB'\fR) and hyphen (\fB-\fR) are excluded.
.TP
.B \-\-debug
Enable debug output.  When this flag is set the program prints a
diagnostic line to \fBstderr\fR for each generated name, showing the
raw adjective, noun and the files they originated from.
.TP
.B \-\-help
Show a short help message and exit.
.SH CONFIGURATION
The behaviour of \fBnamgen\fR can also be controlled through environment
variables.  Command‑line options always take precedence over these
variables.
.TP
.B ASSETS_DIR
Path to the assets directory containing the \fBadjectives\fR and
\fBnouns\fR subfolders (default: \fI./assets\fR).
.TP
.B ADJ_FILE
Path to the default adjectives file (overrides \fBADJ_FOLDER\fR if set).
.TP
.B NOUN_FILE
Path to the default nouns file (overrides \fBNOUN_FOLDER\fR if set).
.TP
.B ADJ_FOLDER
Path to the adjectives folder (default: \fIassets/adjectives\fR).
.TP
.B NOUN_FOLDER
Path to the nouns folder (default: \fIassets/nouns\fR).
.TP
.B NULL_SEPARATOR
Enable null‑separator mode when set to \fBtrue\fR (equivalent to
\fB\-\-null-separator\fR).
.TP
.B SEPARATOR
Custom separator string (equivalent to \fB\-\-separator\fR).
.TP
.B CAPCASING
Enable capcasing style when set to \fBtrue\fR (equivalent to
\fB\-\-capcasing\fR).
.TP
.B CAMELCASING
Enable camel‑casing style when set to \fBtrue\fR (equivalent to
\fB\-\-camelcasing\fR).
.TP
.B EXCLUDE
String of characters to exclude (equivalent to \fB\-\-exclude\fR).
.SH EXAMPLES
Generate five random names:
.PP
.nf
   namgen \-c 5
.fi
.PP
Use custom word lists and produce CamelCase output:
.PP
.nf
   namgen \-a custom_adjectives.txt \-n custom_nouns.txt \\
          \-\-camelcasing \-\-count 10
.fi
.PP
Set a custom separator via an environment variable:
.PP
.nf
   SEPARATOR='_' namgen
.fi
.PP
Generate names with no vowels (exclude a, e, i, o, u):
.PP
.nf
   namgen \-\-exclude 'aeiou' \-\-count 8
.fi
.PP
Enable debug output to see the source files for each name:
.PP
.nf
   namgen \-\-debug \-\-count 3
.fi
